<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="696" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="96.[2051,2646,2544,2968]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">
Originally considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[2052,2189,2776,2810]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Melomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lutillus">M. lutillus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1951" box="[2208,2357,2776,2810]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Melomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="frigicola">M. frigicola</taxonomicName>
was elevated to species rank in 1996 by J. I. Menzies, who included it, as well as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[2388,2531,2863,2888]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Melomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lutillus">M. lutillus</taxonomicName>
, in the “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gould" authorityYear="1852" box="[2064,2242,2894,2928]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cervinipes">M. cervinipes</taxonomicName>
division.” P. H. Fabre and colleagues in 2017 also described some
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="96.[1436,2643,2972,3478]" box="[1439,1972,2972,3006]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">characters for this species. Monotypic.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="696" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" targetBox="[843,847,419,444]" targetPageId="97">
<paragraph blockId="96.[1436,2643,2972,3478]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1438,1614,3016,3045]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">Distribution.</emphasis>
N slopes of the Snow (= Sudirman) Mts and nearby Baliem River, WC New Guinea.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="696" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="96.[1436,2643,2972,3478]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1438,1690,3091,3125]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 101-135 mm, tail 122-136 mm, ear 12-14 mm, hindfeet 23-29 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Snow Mountains Grassland Mosaic-tailed Rat is a small-sized 
<taxonomicName box="[2040,2149,3169,3203]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Melomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Melomys</taxonomicName>
. Upperparts are yellow brown, with gray-buff to pure white ventral coloration. Tail is of about same size as orslightly longer than head-body length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1438,2423,3287,3321]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="96.[1436,2643,2972,3478]" box="[1438,2423,3287,3321]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1438,1549,3287,3321]" pageId="96" pageNumber="696">Habitat.</emphasis>
Secondary forests and grasslands between 600 m and 2200 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
